                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d808">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">763.72115/3731: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in France</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Wallace</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Paris</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1920-05-14T23:00:00+01:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">May 14, 1920—11 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/>[Received May 14—9 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1154. Mission. Your 917, May 12, noon. In response to my inquiry at Ambassadors
                    Conference this morning Laroche<note n="63" xml:id="d808fn63">Jules Alfred
                        Laroche, of the French Ministry of Foreign Affairs.</note> stated that
                    French Government had expressed willingness to facilitate <pb facs="0772"
                        n="672" xml:id="pg_672"/> transfer of Bela Kun and other Communists to
                    Soviet Russia provided Soviets permitted French citizens to leave Russia.
                    Agreement similar to British agreement with Soviets was being negotiated for
                    repatriation of French citizens held in Russia but Soviets were putting
                    obstacles in the way. He added that Hungarian Government might make objections.
                    My British, Italian and Japanese colleagues undertook to inquire of their
                    respective Governments when information received. Question will come up again in
                    the conference.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Wallace</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
